The paper deals with a communication channel with delayed feedback and proposes an adaptive and causal network coding algorithm with forward error correction. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the performance of the proposed algorithm in terms of throughput and delay, which are key metrics in the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper also mentions the potential application of the algorithm in ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC), which falls under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of feedback acknowledgments to learn the erasure pattern of the channel, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the comparison of the proposed algorithm with selective repeat (SR)-ARQ, which is a protocol used in Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC).
